At JPM we are extremely careful with AI deployment because we are so heavily regulated, and a hallucination is not just a minor error, it can create billions in capital impact and serious reputational risk.  For example, I work in policy where I interpret gray areas of the rules and advise desks on structuring transactions in a capital efficient way. We trained a model on the regulations and quickly noticed it produced inaccurate outputs, which in our world could lead a desk to make a decision that ties up significant capital unnecessarily. Once we saw that risk, we tightened access because we do not want traders relying on an LLM as if it were a policy expert, so for now it functions more like a very controlled research assistant than a decision maker.  Also, do not be too hard on yourself about the first session. There are usually a few strong takeaways even when it feels messy in the moment, and it sounds like you already refined the second one nicely. Please do send over the echo360.

SUBJECT: AI upskilling
CONTENT: Hi Sunny,  As it happens, I was about to view your YT video on How AI actually works (I am immersing myself in the damn future) :)  As Ian mentioned, I am researching how to upskill our ~100 Tier 1 team. I joined the company (https://clarivate.com/life-sciences-healthcare/) in October. One of our corporate goals for 2025 was to fully incorporate AI in our products/solutions (we have a Saas-based portfolio) - which has been kicked off and going ok to well to too slow - depends on who you are talking to. MY remit is to upskill our team, and we have a mixed back of users, ranging from the "never used" to "everyday user". We also have a host of issues ranging from a lack of governance to nebulosity re: usage and policies, no knowledge management, no use-case support... in short, we are supremely lacking. Most users have the free Copilot with our MS 365, and only a very few have the Pro version. Needless to say, output with the free version is poor. I myself prefer Claude, even the free version.   All this to say that I would love to have an exploratory conversation with you. Caveat #1 being that an internal team has already short listed 3 vendors/training partners - Eularis, Intuitionlabs and Founderz - for AI literacy and culture transformation - but nothing has moved ahead on that front. Caveat #2 - the CEO of our group has allocated a budget (hashtag#s are fluid) but haven't signed off on one yet. My agenda, if you will, for a call with you will be for research, and not hiring (yet, unless a budget appears!).  This week is packed already but would love 30 mins with you next week, if you are amenable. Please provide me with your availability for a Teams call. My email is maya.viswanath@clarivate.com and I am in EST.   Looking forward to hearing from you.  My best, Maya

Hey Sunny, good to hear from you. Cool to hear about the early stage opportunity. What are the cofounders' backgrounds? I can't really say there have been many hard resources (books, blog posts etc) that I have used to "be a CTO". Personally, the title "CTO" in an early stage company (including Nuvocargo) is a little bit silly and overblown. For the first 9 months, I was basically a cofounder and "engineer #1" ‚Äî a builder, rather than a "CTO". For the next 9 months, I was still building, but also playing "engineering manager" as our team was growing. For the last year, the majority of my time has been spent on growing our technical teams from a few people to dozens of people while playing a bit of a technical architect/mentor role. I wouldn't overthink the role or title to begin with. In early stage companies "CTO" basically just means you're the most technical person in the company and you're going to do whatever needs to be done to help the company succeed from a technical lens.

We believe that the gauntlet of growing up gay creates a gritty resilience that makes LGBTQ+ leaders unstoppable. CONVERSATION TITLE: Full Stack Ruby on Rails Engineer: Up to $200K+Equity
SUBJECT: Full Stack Ruby on Rails Engineer: Up to $200K+Equity
CONTENT: Hi Sunny!  An NYC-based, fin-tech start-up is seeking a Full Stack Ruby on Rails developer to help complete the build-out and maintenance of their existing features while conceptualizing and deploying brand new features on their customer-facing application and back-end portal. As one of the founding members of the engineering team, you will work directly with the CTO, helping bring both the company and your ideas to life. SUBJECT: Tookan Insurance
CONTENT: Hi, Sunny!  I see that you are a software engineer and love entrepreneurship. I found you via Y combinator's founder matching program and wanted to reach out to you on here! I have a unique idea of an online insurance app that delivers a new way to pay for insurance in today's world.  I want to see if you are interested in teaming up on the venture as a co-founder and CTO?  There will be no more monthly premiums with this new kind of insurance product.  Example: Have you ever wanted auto insurance without paying a monthly premium? That is what this new insurance product would deliver. People get to have insurance without realizing they are paying for it.  You have most insurance companies that charge a high monthly calculated premium in which many people can't afford & you have other insurance companies that charge per mile in which no one wants to track how much they drive to afford their insurance every month. I have another unique way to pay for a policy that is affordable & more practical for anyone to have a policy with us.  Food for thought: "Global insurance premiums now top $5 trillion annually. Capture just 1% of that, and you have a $50 billion revenue stream. Secure just 0.1% and it's still $5 billion." Source: https://news.crunchbase.com/news/as-insurtech-exits-spike-more-vc-money-piles-into-the-space/  Please if you are interested, I'm looking forward to hearing from you asap.  Thanks Brad.

SUBJECT: June is Pride Month: The LGBT financial literacy gap
CONTENT: Hi Stephanie,  We need to talk about the major financial literacy gap within the LGBT community as personal finance is rarely discussed in queer spaces.  In queer spaces, there is strong rejection of capitalism, and many within the community do not feel safe in traditional personal finance spaces. These factors have resulted in an overall apathy towards anything personal finance.  Heres‚Äô why the importance of financial literacy in the LGBT community cannot be stressed enough: 1. There are still many political challenges that the LGBT community face in the US despite the progress we‚Äôve made in the media landscape. Economic power is political power. 2. Many LGBT friendly neighborhoods have been subject to gentrification across the country therefore it simply costs more money sustain a lifestyle in an LGBT friendly locale. 3. Still to this day, many in the LGBT community are estranged from their families which underscores the need to have a financial nest egg especially through retirement.  I started a Tiktok (@themoneygay) and am struck at the positive response to personal finance advice being administered from a gay voice. As someone who started my career on Wall Street, never thought I‚Äôd see the day that my queer identity would actually enhance my financial authority!  If you‚Äôre interested in diving deeper, I‚Äôm happy to provide more commentary on this as well as access to members in the LGBT community within my network who are ready to discuss!   More About Me: ‚Ä¢ I‚Äôve worked in the personal finance industry for the better part of a decade ‚Ä¢ Served as a member of Master Your Money Council in Business Insider last year and been featured a few times ‚Ä¢ Started a TikTok (@themoneygay) where my first video went viral (over 220k views) focused personal finance ‚Ä¢ CFA Charterholder ‚Ä¢ Worked on Wall Street for several years ‚Ä¢ Currently founder of a digital personal finance company, Clasp

Hi Sunny,  Great to meet you, too! Your app sounds like something I would LOVE to have! This project is right up my alley, too. I‚Äôve recently worked with two early age startups on their brand identity - SIPTIP, a customized wine delivery service for millennials, and Ning Solutions, a consulting agency. Both companies wanted a fresh and modern look, so for the logos we went for flat designs with icons that represented the personality of their brands. I also developed the larger visual identity systems for these companies - color palette, imagery selection, typography, etc.  Here is my portfolio if you want to check out my work: https://indd.adobe.com/view/93abf91f-8d4f-49b8-b3a0-a6fe7fd56679  Regarding my process, I would start by working with you to understand your brand - who your target is, what your brand‚Äôs personality is like, what message you want to send, etc. We‚Äôll also review other logos and brands that you like/dislike, so that I understand what your aesthetic tastes are. It sounds like you‚Äôve already put thought into this, which is great and may speed this part up, I would just want to make sure we‚Äôre on completely the same page before the designing starts.  Once we‚Äôre aligned on the vision, I‚Äôll start designing! Depending on your budget, I usually provide up to 3 logo options for you to choose from. For each option, I can show you different color variations and mock ups so that you can envision what they‚Äôll look like in real life applications. Once we decide on a logo, I‚Äôll provide you all the assets and files you need. Depending on your schedule, the whole process may take around 2-4 weeks.  As for pricing, I charge up to $900 (more if you want to get into a visual identity system). Pricing will really depend on how in-depth you want to go with the above process, how detailed you want to get with the design, how many revisions or options you want to look at, how long you plan to use the logo, etc. I‚Äôm happy to work within your budget and come up with a plan that works for us both.  I hope this helps, let me know if you have other questions or want to hop on a call and chat further.  Thanks!  Alex¬†‚Ä® alholness@gmail.com www.alexandraholness.com

SUBJECT: RE: Reaching Out from Flatiron
CONTENT: Hi Nksoi:  Great meeting you as well! For my career before Bloomberg, I did both front end and back end--I tried to keep a good balance of both. After doing that over a few years, I slowly developed a preference.¬†  When starting out, I always recommend newcomers to the field to take a Full Stack position so that way they get exposure to both. However, it depends on what's available and sometimes it may not be an option. If you do select a back-end only job starting out then it would be a good idea to work on front-end projects on the side (and vice versa if you got a front-end job).  Hope that helps. Good luck!  -Sunny

CONTENT: Hi Lauren: Again, so great to hear from you! To give you a little more color, I'm working on a Personal Finance solution focused on empowering millennials around their finacnes. While there are many PFM solutions in the market, the emphasis here is on behavioral change as well as appealing to the underlying emotions around money. I spent a good part of last year interviewing dozens of millennials across the country learning more about attitudes and habits around finances and have gained a ton of interesting insights that is informing the direction of the product.  I have completed a prototype and already received a super positive response! This is both from users as well as the multiple VCs that I have relationships with--the timing is great for something like this. Ultimately, I'm motivated in really making a difference and empowering people around money which historically has been a tabboo subject of discussion.  I'd love to chat some more to discuss further and to learn more about you! I hang out in Brooklyn a lot, so open to doing coffee if you are. :-)

Thanks for connecting with me. Here are some questions I had about DBC.  - Do you know the employment statistics for DBC graduates that sought jobs in NYC, specifically, the employment rates 3 months post DBC and the average salary?  - Upon DBC, would you say you had the skills to prototype (aka build with code) a web startup idea all on your own?  - Can you name specific instructors at DBC that were good at discovering what you didn't know something and why you didn't know it?  - Can you name a time where you really hit the wall during DBC and what DBC did to help you overcome it?  - Did anybody drop out during your cohort? Do you know the reasons why they dropped out? Would you be able to put me in contact with those who dropped out?  - Would you do DBC again? Is there something else you would have tried before DBC to learn to program?  Thanks for your insight. This will help me decide if DBC is right for me.  -- Peter

Hey AJ:  First off, let me just congratulate u on your decision and being accepted! I really am very excited for you! You'll probably be seeing me around campus as I'll be a coach!  My sister and I started Zoraab when we were both in Finance actually. I didn't have any coding background but the whole process of learning on my own as I built my site was such a fun experience for me and just affirmed that I would love being a full on developer. Initially, doing DBC was a strategic decision for the business, but the reality is that it goes way beyond just my business, but rather gaining skills that I can apply to any business.  As far as prep, of course go through in depth the prep work they give you. The truth is that the curriculum is always changing to keep up with the market, so whatever they've assigned you in phase 0 has been specifically selected to prepare you for DBC. Also I would highly recommend getting up and running with blogging. Everyone who really took advantage of blogging not only were able to really make sense of all they learned, but it proved to be very beneficial when it came to looking for jobs.  So tell me more about ur background. What made you decide to come to DBC?  -Sunny  Sent from LinkedIn for iPhone http://lnkd.in/ios

Hey AJ:    Thanks so much! Are you still at DBC, which location?    DBC was the BEST decision of my life! I like finance but felt entirely paralyzed with by the fact that all these really cool things were happening in all these other industries and I had no way to participate since I had no coding background. Going to DBC was an amazing experience, very happy I did it.    -Sunny

Hey Sunny - I have nothing but good things to say about DBC.  My situation was a bit different from many others who do such programs as my core intention was not to come out and work as a junior developer.  My motivation for going was to learn enough about web app development to be able to build a little bit and, more importantly, be able to work with development teams effectively.  Another program to consider is gSchool, run out of Denver.  It's actually run out of the co-working space I work from, and the current cohort (their 1st) is in their sixth week.  Seems pretty intense and I imagine all of these students will come out quite further down the road than Devbootcamp students.  Best of luck with your decisions.    Best,  Brian

Thanks, Sunny -------------------- Hi Sunny,  I remember this past year in my Consumer Behavior class, our professor had us do an exercise to help out one of her students.  She wanted us to come up with "things that make you stand out, but that nobody sees."  The point was to take the student's product and use parallel, but unrelated concepts for branding purposes.  She didn't tell us the product until the end.  It turned out to be crazy, fun socks.  I hadn't heard of Zoraab until recently and now every time I'm on the internet, I see an ad for it.  I was trying to learn more about the company but there isn't really too much information on the company workings.  I graduated from Stern in May with my MBA in marketing and brand strategy and my professional background is in operations and investment banking. I left my company, McMaster Carr, a couple of weeks ago and I'm interested in learning more about the world of start-ups.  I realize you are likely not hiring at this point, but I'd love to learn more the company and possibly do some pro bono work to gain some experience in brand marketing if you'd be interested.  I'm really impressed with the advertising penetration.  The sites that I've seen the ads on have been pretty diverse in content. I'm also happy to help from an operations/distribution standpoint if that's relevant for you.  Hope to hear from you soon! Mansi

CONVERSATION TITLE: Forrester: How & Why Collaboration Future-Proofs Businesses
CONTENT:
Dear Sunny,


Atlassian partnered with Forrester to research how to future-proof businesses, and I‚Äôm sending you the report for sharing with your teams. 


The report dives into how enterprise IT leaders leverage high-bandwidth collaboration to drive innovation and deliver on the promise of digital transformation. Given the unique time we‚Äôre in, the survey placed emphasis on how teamwork will evolve from where we are today, into the future.


The report unpacks three key findings:

  • Enterprises investing in high-bandwidth collaboration are rewarded with outsized results - an average of $330 million in additional revenue from their collaboration efforts
  • Investing in innovation practices is vital for delivering the results you need today, and for creating the business you want to be in tomorrow
  • Organizations deploying work management solutions will be the best prepared to compete and win in a post-pandemic world

The free report is available for download here (don‚Äôt worry, I don‚Äôt want your email address!). I hope the insights are helpful as you continue to drive your business into this new age of work. Thanks!


Robert Chatwani, CMO, Atlassian

We‚Äôre bullish on the Charlotte region ‚Äî a vibrant, 15-county area surrounding the nation‚Äôs second-fastest-growing city ‚Äî and our collaborative, public-private partnerships give us good reason:
